t = James B. |last = Meigs |year = 2006 |url = http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/research/4199607.html |title = The Conspiracy Industry |work = Popular Mechanics |publisher = [[Hearst Communications|Hearst Communications, Inc.]] |accessdate = 13 October 2006 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20061024062122/http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/research/4199607.html |archivedate = 24 October 2006 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Nefes | first1 = T\u00fcrkay Salim | year = 2012 | title = The history of the social constructions of D\u00f6nmes | journal = Journal of Historical Sociology | volume = 25 | issue = 3| pages = 413\u201339 | doi = 10.1111/j.1467-6443.2012.01434.x }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Nefes | first1 = T\u00fcrkay Salim | year = 2013 | title = 'Political parties' perceptions and uses of anti-Semitic conspiracy theories in Turkey' | journal = The Sociological Review | volume = 61 | issue = 2| pages = 247\u201364 | doi = 10.1111/1467-954X.12016 }}\n* Oliver, J. Eric, and Thomas J. Wood. \"Conspiracy theories and the paranoid style (s) of mass opinion.\" ''American Journal of Political Science'' 58.4 (2014): 952-966.  [http://hon3397p.wp.txstate.edu/files/2015/08/OliverWood.pdf online]\n* {{cite news |last = Parsons |first = Charlotte |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/1561199.stm |title = Why we need conspiracy theories |work = BBC News \u2013 Americas |publisher = BBC |accessdate=26 June 2006 |date=24 September 2001}}\n* {{cite book|author=Pipes, Daniel|year=1998|title=The Hidden Hand: Middle East Fears of Conspiracy|location=New York|publisher=St. Martin's Press|isbn=978-0-312-17688-4|title-link=The Hidden Hand: Middle East Fears of Conspiracy}}\n* {{cite book|author=Pipes, Daniel|year=1997|title=Conspiracy: How the Paranoid Style Flourishes and Where It Comes From|location=New York|publisher=The Free Press|isbn=978-0-684-87111-0|title-link=Conspiracy: How the Paranoid Style Flourishes and Where It Comes From}}\n* {{cite journal |title=Popper Revisited, or What Is Wrong With Conspiracy Theories? |journal=Philosophy of the Social Sciences |year=1995 |last=Pigden |first=Charles |volume=25 |issue=1 |pages=3\u201334 |doi=10.1177/004839319502500101}}<!--|accessdate=13 April 2015 -->\n* {{cite book|author=Sagan, Carl|author-link=Carl Sagan|year=1996|title=The Demon-Haunted World: Science as a Candle in the Dark|location=New York|publisher=The Random House|isbn=978-0-394-53512-8}}\n* Slosson, W. [https://archive.org/stream/unpopularreview07newy#page/394/mode/2up ''\"The 'Conspiracy' Superstition,\"''] The Unpopular Review, Vol. VII, N\u00b0. 14, 1917.\n* Sunstein, Cass R., and Adrian Vermeule. \"Conspiracy theories: Causes and cures.\" ''Journal of Political Philosophy'' 17.2 (2009): 202\u2013227. [http://www.ask-force.org/web/Discourse/Sunstein-Conspiracy-Theories-2009.pdf  online]\n* Uscinski, Joseph E. and Joseph M. Parent, ''American Conspiracy Theories'' (2014) [https://www.amazon.com/dp/0199351813/ excerpt]\n* Uscinski, Joseph E. \"The 5 Most Dangerous Conspiracy Theories of 2016' [http://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2016/08/conspiracy-theories-2016-donald-trump-hillary-clinton-214183  ''POLITICO Magazine'' (Aug 22, 2016)]\n* {{cite book|author1=Vankin, Jonathan|author-link=Jonathan Vankin|author2=John Whalen|year=2004|title=The 80 Greatest Conspiracies of All Time|location=New York|publisher=Citadel Press|isbn=978-0-8065-2531-0}}\n* Wood, Gordon S. \"Conspiracy and the paranoid style: causality and deceit in the eighteenth century.\" ''William and Mary Quarterly''   (1982): 402\u2013441. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/1919580 in jstor]\n* Zwierlein, Cornel  / Beatrice de Graaf (eds.) [https://www.gesis.org/en/hsr/full-text-archive/2013/381-security-and-conspiracy/ ''Security and Conspiracy in History, 16th to 21st Century'']. [[Historical Social Research]] 38, Special Issue, 2013\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|conspiracy theory}}\n{{Commons category|Conspiracy theories}}\n* [http://iipdigital.usembassy.gov/st/english/texttrans/2009/07/20090714143549iaecnav0.4049581.html State Department's Todd Leventhal Discusses Conspiracy Theories], 2009, U.S. Department of State's Bureau of International Information Programs usembassy.gov\n* [http://iipdigital.usembassy.gov/st/english/texttrans/2006/01/20060120112446atlahtnevel0.627331.html September 11 Conspiracy Theories: Confused stories continue], 2006, usembassy.gov\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/26/magazine/why-rational-people-buy-into-conspiracy-theories.html Why Rational People Buy Into Conspiracy Theories], Maggie Koerth-Baker, 21 May 2013, NYT.\n* {{cite web |url=http://www.guatemala-times.com/opinion/syndicated/the-next-wave/483-a-conspiracy-so-immense.html |title=Analysis of the appeal of conspiracy theories with suggestions for more accurate ad hoc internet reporting of them |author=Naomi Wolf |author-link=Naomi Wolf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081102075945/http://www.guatemala-times.com/opinion/syndicated/the-next-wave/483-a-conspiracy-so-immense.html |archivedate=2 November 2008  }}\n* {{cite journal |url=http://www.mediatropes.com/index.php/Mediatropes/article/view/5342/2243 |journal=MediaTropes eJournal |author=Stuart J. Murray |title=Editorial Introduction: 'Media Tropes' |volume=2 |issue=1 |year=2009 |pages=i\u2013x}}\n* [http://www.publiceye.org/tooclose/conspiracism.html Conspiracism], Political Research Associates\n\n{{Conspiracy theories}}\n{{Pseudoscience}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Conspiracy Theory}}\n[[Category:Conspiracy theories| ]]\n[[Category:Fringe theory]]\n[[Category:Pejoratives]]\n[[Category:Barriers to critical thinking]]\n", "name_user": "Jammie23", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eRothbard: shallow vs. deep)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Conspiracy_theory"}
{"title_page": "Day-In Day-Out", "text_new": "{{For|other songs of the same name|Day In, Day Out (disambiguation){{!}}Day In, Day Out}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Day-In Day-Out\n| cover      = Bowie_DayInDayOut.jpg\n| alt        = A picture of David Bowie jumping in front of a colorful room full of art and props.\n| caption    = Cover artwork used to commercialize [[12\"]] editions of the single.\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[David Bowie]]\n| album      = [[Never Let Me Down]]\n| B-side     = Julie\n| released   = {{start date|df=yes|1987|3|23}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[gramophone record|7\"]]|[[12-inch single|12\"]]}}\n| recorded   = Autumn 1986<br>[[Mountain Studios]]<br>([[Montreux]], Switzerland)\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 4:38 (Album version)<br />4:14 (Single version)\n| label      = [[EMI]]\n| writer     = David Bowie\n| producer   = {{hlist|David Bowie|[[David Richards (record producer)|David Richards]]}}\n| prev_title = [[When the Wind Blows (song)|When the Wind Blows]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = [[Time Will Crawl]]\n| next_year  = 1987\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|zl9BLmwFi0U|\"Day-In Day-Out\"}}}}\n}}\n'''\"Day-In Day-Out\"''' is a song recorded by English singer [[David Bowie]], serving as the opening track for his seventeenth studio album, ''[[Never Let Me Down]]'' (1987). It was issued as a single on 23 March 1987 ahead of the record's release. The recording was solely written by Bowie, while production was handled by him along with [[David Richards (record producer)|David Richards]]. An [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] track, \"Day-In Day-Out\" criticizes the treatment of the homeless in the United States at that time, and deals with the depths to which a young mother sinks to feed her child.\n\nAn accompanying music video for the single was shot in 1987, being banned by some stations as a result of its content, although it was still nominated for a [[1987 MTV Video Music Awards|1987 MTV Video Music award]] in the category of \"Best Male Video\". Commercially, \"Day-In Day-Out\" was the most successful single from ''Never Let Me Down'', peaking at number 17 in the United Kingdom as well as charting within the top 40 in several other countries.\n\nA re-engineered version of the song that includes Bowie's original vocals, some original and new instrumentation, and new mastering was released in 2018 as part of the album ''[[Never Let Me Down#Never Let Me Down 2018|Never Let Me Down 2018]]'', part of the ''[[Loving the Alien (1983-1988)]]'' box set.\n\n==Background and release==\n\"Day-In Day-Out\" was written by Bowie at his home in [[Montreux]], Switzerland, along with most of the rest of ''Never Let Me Down'' in mid-1986.<ref name=\"MusicianMag\">{{Cite book | last=Isler| first=Scott| title=David Bowie Opens Up - A Little | journal=Musician| issue=106|date=August 1987 | pages=60\u201373}}</ref> It was recorded in the autumn of 1986 at [[Mountain Studios]] in the same city.<ref name=\"credits\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Never Let Me Down |year=1987 |type=Liner notes/ CD booklet |publisher=[[EMI]]}}</ref> The singer penned the song out of concern for the treatment of the homeless in the United States,<ref name=StockholmPress /> a foray into social commentary that he would further pursue with his grunge-precursor band [[Tin Machine]] two years later.<ref name=\"tcdbeu\">{{cite book | title=\"The Complete David Bowie New Edition: Expanded and Updated\" | last=Pegg | first=Nicholas | date=October 2016 | publisher=Titan Books}}</ref>\n\nMusically, the recording is an [[R&B]] song,<ref name=\"WMDB\">{{cite book|title=The Words and Music of David Bowie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C6bz2BFdPawC&pg=PA93 |accessdate=24 April 2013|last=Perone|first=James|page=93|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]}}</ref> being reminiscent of some of the singer's R&B work in the 1970s.<ref name=\"BLTA\">{{cite book|title=Bowie: Loving the Alien|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OomyGN_btTQC&pg=PA264 |accessdate=24 April 2013|last=Sandford|first=Christopher|page=264}}</ref> One author said that it is \"an example of Bowie's strength in the R&B genre.\"<ref name=\"WMDB\" /> The lyrics of the song were compared by one writer to those of [[Dolly Parton]]'s \"[[9 to 5 (Dolly Parton song)|9 to 5]]\" (1980), and deal with the depths a young mother has to sink to feed her child.<ref name=\"WMDB\" /> Bowie claimed the song was selected as the lead-off single for ''Never Let Me Down'' \"more as a statement of energy\" about the album, as opposed to directly trying for a chart-topping single.<ref name=\"MusicianMag\" /> It was released on 23 March 1987 by [[EMI]] on multiple [[7\"]] and [[12\"]] single formats, featuring B-side single \"Julie\".<ref name=\"7 inch\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Day-In Day-Out |year=1987 |type=Liner notes |publisher=[[EMI]] (Barcode: 5099920171377)}}</ref><ref name=\"12 inch\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Day-In Day-Out |year=1987 |type=Liner notes |publisher=[[EMI]] (Barcode: 077771923418)}}</ref> A video EP was also distributed that year.<ref name=\"tcdbeu\"/> The single was further added to several compilations, including ''[[Bowie: The Singles 1969-1993]]'' (1993), ''[[The Singles Collection (David Bowie album)|The Singles Collection]]'' (1993), ''[[Bowie \u2013 The Video Collection]]'' (1993), ''[[Best of Bowie]]'' (2002), ''[[The Platinum Collection (David Bowie album)|The Platinum Collection]]'' (2005) and ''[[The Best of David Bowie 1980/1987|The Best of David Bowie 1980\u20131987]]'' (2007).<ref>Sources for the addition of \"Day-In Day-Out\" on various media:\n* {{cite book | title=\"The Complete David Bowie New Edition: Expanded and Updated\" | last=Pegg | first=Nicholas | date=October 2016 | publisher=Titan Books}}\n* {{Cite AV media notes |title=Glass Spider |title-link=Glass Spider |year=1988 |type=Liner notes}}\n* {{Cite AV media notes |title=Bowie: The Singles 1969-1993 |title-link=Bowie: The Singles 1969-1993 |year=1993 |type=Liner notes}}\n* {{Cite AV media notes |title=The Singles Collection |title-link=The Singles Collection (David Bowie album) |year=1993 |type=Liner notes}}\n* {{Cite AV media notes |title=Bowie \u2013 The Video Collection |title-link=Bowie \u2013 The Video Collection |year=1993 |type=Liner notes}}\n* {{Cite AV media notes |title=Best of Bowie |title-link=Best of Bowie |year=2002 |type=Liner notes}}\n* {{Cite AV media notes |title=The Platinum Collection |title-link=The Platinum Collection (David Bowie album) |year=2005 |type=Liner notes}}\n* {{Cite AV media notes |title=The Best of David Bowie 1980\u20131987 |title-link=The Best of David Bowie 1980/1987 |year=2005 |type=Liner notes}}</ref>\n\nA Spanish-language version of \"Day-In-Day-Out\", known as \"Al Alba\" or \"Dia Tras Dia\", was recorded in 1987 in order to boost interest in Bowie's first-ever concerts in Spain as part of his [[Glass Spider Tour]] (1987). It earned a single airing on Spanish radio prior to the concerts and was never released as a stand-alone single, although it was made available for [[Music download|digital download]] in 2007.<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" />\n\n\"Day-In Day-Out\" was performed live during the Glass Spider Tour (1987), and was included on the concert video release ''[[Glass Spider]]'' (1988).<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" />\n\nRe-recorded and re-mastered versions of \"Day-In Day-Out\" appears in the box set ''[[Loving the Alien (1983-1988)]]'' (2018).<ref name=\"LTA88\">{{cite AV media notes | title=Loving the Alien (1983-1988) | year=2018 | publisher=Parlophone}}</ref> For the re-recorded version of the song, album engineer [[Mario J. McNulty]] discovered from the original master tapes that Bowie had recorded the Borneo Horns ([[Stan Harrison|Stanley Harrison]], [[Lenny Pickett]], Steve Elson and [[Arif Mardin]]) playing live for the song, but had elected to replace them with synthesized horns. McNulty restored the live horns in the new version, saying that the track now had \"one foot in the past and another in the present\".<ref name=\"18rs\">{{citation | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/how-david-bowies-biggest-disappointment-became-a-posthumous-reworked-album-702189/amp/ | title=How David Bowie\u2019s Biggest \u2018Disappointment\u2019 Became a Posthumous, Reworked Album | date=24 July 2018 | accessdate=31 July 2018 | last1=Grow | first1=Kory | last2=Greene | first2=Andy | journal=Rolling Stone}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = Favorable<ref name=allmusicreview>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/day-in-day-out-mt0013926923 | title=David Bowie \"Day-In Day-Out\" Review\" | accessdate=28 October 2013 | first=Ned | last=Raggett|publisher=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref>\n| rev2      = [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]\n| rev2Score = Unfavorable<ref name=pitchforkreview>{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/10274-best-of-bowie-1980-1987/ | title=David Bowie \"Best of Bowie: 1980-1987\" Review | date=6 July 2007 | first=Stuart | last=Berman | accessdate=28 October 2013|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]}}</ref>\n}}\nUpon release, \"Day-In Day-Out\" received mixed reviews from [[Music journalism|music critics]]. Complaints about poor studio production were common,<ref name=BLTA /><ref name=allmusicreview /><ref name=pitchforkreview /><ref name=nyt>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/04/26/arts/david-bowie-mingles-glamour-and-gloom.html | title=David Bowie mingles glamour and gloom | date=26 April 1987 | first=Jon | last=Pareles | accessdate=28 October 2013 | work=The New York Times}}</ref> although publications did find the song to be \"fun\"<ref name=allmusicreview /><ref name=87RSReview>{{cite web | title=\"Never Let Me Down Rolling\" Stone album review | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/never-let-me-down-19870604 | journal=[[Rolling Stone]] | accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> and \"danceable\".<ref name=BLTA /><ref name=Spin87>{{cite journal | journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]| title=''Never Let Me Down'' album review | date=May 1987 | first=Glenn | last=O'Brien | pages=29\u201330 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dNSW1RIkidsC&pg=RA1-PA29&dq=bowie&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JBdwUZjtH4moiAK75YH4Ag&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=bowie&f=false | accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> Bowie biographer [[Nicholas Pegg]] called the track \"frustrating\", for on one hand being \"a pretty fine song\", but on the other, \"[encapsulating] everything that's initially promising but ultimately infuriating\" about the album. He concluded, \"Somewhere in there is a concerted attempt to reclaim Bowie's former territory of guitar-based rock'n'roll, but 'Day-In Day-Out' suffers badly from over-elaboration: it's a slab of 1980s soft-rock which now [in 2016] sounds incredibly dated by comparison with much of Bowie's earlier work.\"<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" />\n\nB-side single \"Julie\" was described by Bowie biographer David Buckley as the \"catchiest\" song of all the tracks from the ''Never Let Me Down'' sessions, and lamented that the recording was relegated to mere B-side status.<ref name=SFDB>{{cite book|title=Strange Fascination: David Bowie: The Definitive Story|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vk-I_ZM_PfwC&pg=PA374 |accessdate=24 April 2013|last=Buckley|first=David|page=374|publisher=[[Random House]]}}</ref> Pegg agreed, calling it \"arguably one of the best tracks from the whole [''Never Let Me Down'' recording] session\", and thought it might have been a hit if Bowie had released it as a single on its own.<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" />\n\n==Music video==\n===Background and development===\nAn accompanying music video for \"Day-In Day-Out\" was shot in [[Los Angeles]] in early 1987, with Bowie claiming it was \"not going to sell the song at all\", and was designed to explore the music video as a storytelling format over promoting the track itself.<ref name=\"MusicianMag\" /> The singer also took a hand in designing and [[storyboard]]ing the visual, saying, \"I do the original drawings, the main shot for every situation, and then the storyboardist puts them into sequence, storyboarding backwards and forwards from that. Then I put in the major camera angles that I think would be interesting or different. And Julien [Temple] puts in his input. I started working this way on the '[[Ashes to Ashes (David Bowie song)|Ashes to Ashes]]' video with [[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]]. It was my first real big attempt and it won awards at the time for being a new way of doing videos.\"<ref name=TW87x>{{cite journal | title=Dave In, Dave Out | journal=Music & Sound Output magazine | date=June 1987}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hollywood_boulevard_from_kodak_theatre.jpg|thumb|250px|right|The music video for \"Day-In Day-Out\" was shot on the [[Hollywood Boulevard]] (''pictured'') at night.<ref name=\"GUK13\"/>]]\n[[Julien Temple]] and Bowie co-directed the video, which made the song's message explicit, showing a young couple's struggle against an uncaring society.<ref name=StockholmPress>{{cite AV media | date=28 March 1987 | title=The Glass Spider Tour Press Conferences (Stockholm)|type=vinyl}}</ref> Bowie worked with Los Angeles theater group \"Skid Row\" to represent the homeless in the video.<ref>{{cite AV media | people=Unknown host | title=Tin Machine (Special) | medium=Television documentary | date=18 October 1991 | location=Copenhagen |minutes=7}}</ref> Tony Selznik taught Bowie to roller skate for the video, recalling in 2013, \"David came across as very humble and in between careers, almost. He was disillusioned with the music industry. I taught him to skate in a parking lot. We shot the video on [[Hollywood Boulevard]] at night, with me in a wig and leather jacket as his double for some scenes. The only bad fall involved the instructor: my wheels came off, I was bleeding everywhere, and David helped me clean up. He was so nice, normal.\"<ref name=GUK13>{{cite journal | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/feb/23/david-bowie-and-me | title=David Bowie and Me | date=22 February 2013 | accessdate=25 June 2013 | journal=[[The Guardian]] | location=London | first=Dave | last=Simpson}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy and recognition===\nThe music video was banned by some TV stations, even after edits removed the female protagonist's heavily implied rape, swapped in an alternate version of a scene where the couple's child spells out \"Mom\", \"Food\" and \"Fuck\" in building blocks (words which represented the child's cycle of dependency; the alternate version had the child spell out the meaningless words \"Mom\", \"Look\" and \"Luck\"),<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" /> and removed a closing scene of a young man urinating on [[Ronald Reagan]]'s star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].<ref name=ct87dido>{{cite journal | url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1987-04-09/features/8701270354_1_david-bowie-video-outlets-absolute-beginners | title=Cleaned Up Bowie`s New Video Is A Hit | date=9 April 1987 | first=Jonathan | last=Taylor | journal=[[Chicago Tribune]] | accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nConcerning the clip's ban, Bowie confessed, \"I think it's ludicrous. [The censors] got caught up in the usual [[Yellow journalism|yellow press]] kind of excitement because of what it looked like instead of what it said.\"<ref name=AmsterdamPress>{{cite AV media | date=30 March 1987 | title=The Glass Spider Tour Press Conferences (Amsterdam)|type=vinyl}}</ref> During the press tour for the [[Glass Spider Tour]], he was asked about the controversy and responded, \"We asked the [Los Angeles] police to work with us and they did very happily. We wanted to indicate how some of the houses for the homeless are removed, so we asked them to bring along the kind of contraption they use [...] it's kind of like a tank with a big battering ram on the end of it. And on the end of the battering ram they've made a little joke. As it goes through the windows it goes 'Have a nice day.' And I pointed out that it would be in the video and they said they were only too pleased to keep it on, so they kept it on. Is that controversial? I don't know.\"<ref name=NewYorkPress>{{cite AV media | date=18 March 1987 | title=The Glass Spider Tour Press Conferences (New York)|type=vinyl}}</ref> The video was nominated for a [[1987 MTV Video Music Awards|1987 MTV Video Music award]] in the category \"Best Male Video\", but lost to [[Peter Gabriel]]'s clip for \"[[Sledgehammer (Peter Gabriel song)|Sledgehammer]]\" (1986).<ref name=mtvvma>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/vma/1987 | title=MTV Video Music Awards 1987 | date=11 September 1987 | accessdate=28 October 2013|publisher=[[MTV]]}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll lyrics written by Bowie, while remixes produced by [[Shep Pettibone]], except for the \"Groucho\" mix, which was remixed by Paul \"Groucho\" Smykle.<ref name=\"tcdbeu\"/> A limited edition release (EAX 230) of the second 7\" single issued in the United Kingdom contained a 7\" red vinyl disc in a numbered box with a set of stickers and a photo booklet.<ref name=\"12 inch\"/> The video EP is the sole source of the unedited version of the \"Day-In Day-Out\" and \"[[Loving the Alien]]\" videos. While the latter includes a shot of Bowie with a nosebleed, the edited versions of both visuals appear in later video releases.<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" />\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* '''UK 7\" single''' <ref name=\"7 inch\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=David Bowie \u2013 Day-In Day-Out |url=https://www.discogs.com/David-Bowie-Day-In-Day-Out/master/51369 |website=Discogs |accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Single edit) \u2013 4:14\n# \"Julie\" \u2013 3:40\n* '''UK & worldwide 12\" single 1'''<ref name=\"12 inch\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=David Bowie \u2013 Day-In Day-Out |url=https://www.discogs.com/David-Bowie-Day-In-Day-Out/master/51369 |website=Discogs |accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dance Mix) \u2013 7:15\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dub Mix) \u2013 7:17\n# \"Julie\" \u2013 3:40\n* '''UK & worldwide 12\" single 2'''<ref>{{cite web|title=David Bowie \u2013 Day-In Day-Out |url=https://www.discogs.com/David-Bowie-Day-In-Day-Out/master/51369 |website=Discogs |accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Remix [aka Groucho Mix]) \u2013 6:30\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dub Mix) \u2013 7:17\n# \"Julie\" \u2013 3:40\n* '''US 12\" single'''<ref>{{cite web|title=David Bowie \u2013 Day-In Day-Out |url=https://www.discogs.com/David-Bowie-Day-In-Day-Out/master/51369 |website=Discogs |accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Groucho Mix [aka Remix]) \u2013 6:30\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dance Mix) \u2013 7:15\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Single edit) \u2013 4:14\n# \"Julie\" \u2013 3:40\n* '''US 12\" promo single'''<ref name=\"US2\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Day-In Day-Out |year=1987 |type=Liner notes |publisher=[[EMI]] (Kat.-Nr.: SPRO 9996/9997)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=David Bowie \u2013 Day-In Day-Out |url=https://www.discogs.com/David-Bowie-Day-In-Day-Out/master/51369 |website=Discogs |accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (7\" Dance Edit) \u2013 3:35\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dance Mix) \u2013 7:15\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Edited Dance Mix) \u2013 4:30\n{{col-2}}\n* '''Video EP'''<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" />\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (video)\n# \"Loving the Alien\" (video)\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dance Version) (video)\n* '''UK digital download''' (2007)<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=David Bowie \u2013 Day-In Day-Out |url=https://www.discogs.com/David-Bowie-Day-In-Day-Out/master/51369 |website=Discogs |accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n# \"Al Alba\" [aka Spanish Language version of Day-In Day-Out) \u2013 5:37\n# \"Julie\" \u2013 3:40\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dance Mix) \u2013 7:15\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dub Mix) \u2013 7:17\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (12\" Groucho Mix) \u2013 6:29\n{{col end}}\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Never Let Me Down''.<ref name=\"credits\"/>\n* David Bowie&nbsp;\u2013 [[Singing|vocals]], [[composer]], [[Record producer|producer]]\n* [[David Richards (record producer)|David Richards]]&nbsp;\u2013 producer\n* [[Carlos Alomar]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[guitar]]\n* [[Sid McGinnis]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar\n* [[Erdal Kizilcay]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[bass guitar]], [[Drum kit|drums]], [[Electronic keyboard|keyboards]]\n* [[Robin Clark]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]]\n* [[Diva Gray]]&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n* Loni Groves&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart\n!Peak<br> position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref name=\"auchart\">{{Cite book|title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992]] |last=Kent |first=David |authorlink=David Kent (historian) |publisher=Australian Chart Book |location=[[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives, NSW]] |year=1993 |isbn=0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\" |33\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|25|artist=David Bowie|song=Day-In Day-Out|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|10|artist=David Bowie|song=Day-In Day-Out|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true|refname=\"Flanders\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canada|16|artist=David Bowie|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Finland ([[Suomen virallinen lista]])<ref>{{cite book | first= Timo | last= Pennanen |year= 2006 | title=Sis\u00e4lt\u00e4\u00e4 hitin \u2013 levyt ja esitt\u00e4j\u00e4t Suomen musiikkilistoilla vuodesta 1972 | publisher=Kustannusosakeyhti\u00f6 Otava | location= Helsinki | language= Finnish }}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 6\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|15|artist=David Bowie|song=Day-In Day-Out|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|12|artist=David Bowie|song=Day-In Day-Out|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|5|artist=David Bowie|song=Day-In Day-Out|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Spain ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|AFYVE]])<ref>{{cite book|last=Salaverri|first=Fernando|title=S\u00f3lo \u00e9xitos: a\u00f1o a a\u00f1o, 1959-2002|edition=1st|date=September 2005|publisher=Fundaci\u00f3n Autor-SGAE|location=Spain|isbn=84-8048-639-2}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|14\n|-\n{{singlechart|Switzerland|28|artist=David Bowie|song=Day-In Day-Out|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|UK|17|date=1987-04-12|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardhot100|21|artist=David Bowie|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboarddanceclubplay|10|artist=David Bowie|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" {{singlechart|Billboardmainstreamrock|3|artist=David Bowie|accessdate=8 January 2017}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|West Germany|26|artist=David Bowie|song=Day-In Day-Out|songid=1610|accessdate=2 March 2020|rowheader=true}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* [[Nicholas Pegg|Pegg, Nicholas]], ''The Complete David Bowie New Edition: Expanded and Updated'', Titan Books, 2016, {{ISBN|9781785653650}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|david-bowie|day-in-day-out}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{David Bowie singles}}\n\n[[Category:1987 singles]]\n[[Category:David Bowie songs]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:EMI Records singles]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Julien Temple]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other songs of the same name|Day In, Day Out (disambiguation){{!}}Day In, Day Out}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Day-In Day-Out\n| cover      = Bowie_DayInDayOut.jpg\n| alt        = A picture of David Bowie jumping in front of a colorful room full of art and props.\n| caption    = Cover artwork used to commercialize [[12\"]] editions of the single.\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[David Bowie]]\n| album      = [[Never Let Me Down]]\n| B-side     = Julie\n| released   = {{start date|df=yes|1987|3|23}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[gramophone record|7\"]]|[[12-inch single|12\"]]}}\n| recorded   = Autumn 1986<br>[[Mountain Studios]]<br>([[Montreux]], Switzerland)\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n| length     = 4:38 (Album version)<br />4:14 (Single version)\n| label      = [[EMI]]\n| writer     = David Bowie\n| producer   = {{hlist|David Bowie|[[David Richards (record producer)|David Richards]]}}\n| prev_title = [[When the Wind Blows (song)|When the Wind Blows]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = [[Time Will Crawl]]\n| next_year  = 1987\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|zl9BLmwFi0U|\"Day-In Day-Out\"}}}}\n}}\n'''\"Day-In Day-Out\"''' is a song recorded by English singer [[David Bowie]], serving as the opening track for his seventeenth studio album, ''[[Never Let Me Down]]'' (1987). It was issued as a single on 23 March 1987 ahead of the record's release. The recording was solely written by Bowie, while production was handled by him along with [[David Richards (record producer)|David Richards]]. An [[Rhythm and blues|R&B]] track, \"Day-In Day-Out\" criticizes the treatment of the homeless in the United States at that time, and deals with the depths a young mother has to sink to feed her child.\n\nAn accompanying music video for the single was shot in 1987, being banned by some stations as a result of its content, although it was still nominated for a [[1987 MTV Video Music Awards|1987 MTV Video Music award]] in the category of \"Best Male Video\". Commercially, \"Day-In Day-Out\" was the most successful single from ''Never Let Me Down'', peaking at number 17 in the United Kingdom as well as charting within the top 40 in several other countries.\n\nA re-engineered version of the song that includes Bowie's original vocals, some original and new instrumentation, and new mastering was released in 2018 as part of the album ''[[Never Let Me Down#Never Let Me Down 2018|Never Let Me Down 2018]]'', part of the ''[[Loving the Alien (1983-1988)]]'' box set.\n\n==Background and release==\n\"Day-In Day-Out\" was written by Bowie at his home in [[Montreux]], Switzerland, along with most of the rest of ''Never Let Me Down'' in mid-1986.<ref name=\"MusicianMag\">{{Cite book | last=Isler| first=Scott| title=David Bowie Opens Up - A Little | journal=Musician| issue=106|date=August 1987 | pages=60\u201373}}</ref> It was recorded in the autumn of 1986 at [[Mountain Studios]] in the same city.<ref name=\"credits\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Never Let Me Down |year=1987 |type=Liner notes/ CD booklet |publisher=[[EMI]]}}</ref> The singer penned the song out of concern for the treatment of the homeless in the United States,<ref name=StockholmPress /> a foray into social commentary that he would further pursue with his grunge-precursor band [[Tin Machine]] two years later.<ref name=\"tcdbeu\">{{cite book | title=\"The Complete David Bowie New Edition: Expanded and Updated\" | last=Pegg | first=Nicholas | date=October 2016 | publisher=Titan Books}}</ref>\n\nMusically, the recording is an [[R&B]] song,<ref name=\"WMDB\">{{cite book|title=The Words and Music of David Bowie|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=C6bz2BFdPawC&pg=PA93 |accessdate=24 April 2013|last=Perone|first=James|page=93|publisher=[[Greenwood Publishing Group]]}}</ref> being reminiscent of some of the singer's R&B work in the 1970s.<ref name=\"BLTA\">{{cite book|title=Bowie: Loving the Alien|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OomyGN_btTQC&pg=PA264 |accessdate=24 April 2013|last=Sandford|first=Christopher|page=264}}</ref> One author said that it is \"an example of Bowie's strength in the R&B genre.\"<ref name=\"WMDB\" /> The lyrics of the song were compared by one writer to those of [[Dolly Parton]]'s \"[[9 to 5 (Dolly Parton song)|9 to 5]]\" (1980), and deal with the depths a young mother has to sink to feed her child.<ref name=\"WMDB\" /> Bowie claimed the song was selected as the lead-off single for ''Never Let Me Down'' \"more as a statement of energy\" about the album, as opposed to directly trying for a chart-topping single.<ref name=\"MusicianMag\" /> It was released on 23 March 1987 by [[EMI]] on multiple [[7\"]] and [[12\"]] single formats, featuring B-side single \"Julie\".<ref name=\"7 inch\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Day-In Day-Out |year=1987 |type=Liner notes |publisher=[[EMI]] (Barcode: 5099920171377)}}</ref><ref name=\"12 inch\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Day-In Day-Out |year=1987 |type=Liner notes |publisher=[[EMI]] (Barcode: 077771923418)}}</ref> A video EP was also distributed that year.<ref name=\"tcdbeu\"/> The single was further added to several compilations, including ''[[Bowie: The Singles 1969-1993]]'' (1993), ''[[The Singles Collection (David Bowie album)|The Singles Collection]]'' (1993), ''[[Bowie \u2013 The Video Collection]]'' (1993), ''[[Best of Bowie]]'' (2002), ''[[The Platinum Collection (David Bowie album)|The Platinum Collection]]'' (2005) and ''[[The Best of David Bowie 1980/1987|The Best of David Bowie 1980\u20131987]]'' (2007).<ref>Sources for the addition of \"Day-In Day-Out\" on various media:\n* {{cite book | title=\"The Complete David Bowie New Edition: Expanded and Updated\" | last=Pegg | first=Nicholas | date=October 2016 | publisher=Titan Books}}\n* {{Cite AV media notes |title=Glass Spider |title-link=Glass Spider |year=1988 |type=Liner notes}}\n* {{Cite AV media notes |title=Bowie: The Singles 1969-1993 |title-link=Bowie: The Singles 1969-1993 |year=1993 |type=Liner notes}}\n* {{Cite AV media notes |title=The Singles Collection |title-link=The Singles Collection (David Bowie album) |year=1993 |type=Liner notes}}\n* {{Cite AV media notes |title=Bowie \u2013 The Video Collection |title-link=Bowie \u2013 The Video Collection |year=1993 |type=Liner notes}}\n* {{Cite AV media notes |title=Best of Bowie |title-link=Best of Bowie |year=2002 |type=Liner notes}}\n* {{Cite AV media notes |title=The Platinum Collection |title-link=The Platinum Collection (David Bowie album) |year=2005 |type=Liner notes}}\n* {{Cite AV media notes |title=The Best of David Bowie 1980\u20131987 |title-link=The Best of David Bowie 1980/1987 |year=2005 |type=Liner notes}}</ref>\n\nA Spanish-language version of \"Day-In-Day-Out\", known as \"Al Alba\" or \"Dia Tras Dia\", was recorded in 1987 in order to boost interest in Bowie's first-ever concerts in Spain as part of his [[Glass Spider Tour]] (1987). It earned a single airing on Spanish radio prior to the concerts and was never released as a stand-alone single, although it was made available for [[Music download|digital download]] in 2007.<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" />\n\n\"Day-In Day-Out\" was performed live during the Glass Spider Tour (1987), and was included on the concert video release ''[[Glass Spider]]'' (1988).<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" />\n\nRe-recorded and re-mastered versions of \"Day-In Day-Out\" appears in the box set ''[[Loving the Alien (1983-1988)]]'' (2018).<ref name=\"LTA88\">{{cite AV media notes | title=Loving the Alien (1983-1988) | year=2018 | publisher=Parlophone}}</ref> For the re-recorded version of the song, album engineer [[Mario J. McNulty]] discovered from the original master tapes that Bowie had recorded the Borneo Horns ([[Stan Harrison|Stanley Harrison]], [[Lenny Pickett]], Steve Elson and [[Arif Mardin]]) playing live for the song, but had elected to replace them with synthesized horns. McNulty restored the live horns in the new version, saying that the track now had \"one foot in the past and another in the present\".<ref name=\"18rs\">{{citation | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-features/how-david-bowies-biggest-disappointment-became-a-posthumous-reworked-album-702189/amp/ | title=How David Bowie\u2019s Biggest \u2018Disappointment\u2019 Became a Posthumous, Reworked Album | date=24 July 2018 | accessdate=31 July 2018 | last1=Grow | first1=Kory | last2=Greene | first2=Andy | journal=Rolling Stone}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = Favorable<ref name=allmusicreview>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/song/day-in-day-out-mt0013926923 | title=David Bowie \"Day-In Day-Out\" Review\" | accessdate=28 October 2013 | first=Ned | last=Raggett|publisher=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref>\n| rev2      = [[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]\n| rev2Score = Unfavorable<ref name=pitchforkreview>{{cite web | url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/10274-best-of-bowie-1980-1987/ | title=David Bowie \"Best of Bowie: 1980-1987\" Review | date=6 July 2007 | first=Stuart | last=Berman | accessdate=28 October 2013|publisher=[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]}}</ref>\n}}\nUpon release, \"Day-In Day-Out\" received mixed reviews from [[Music journalism|music critics]]. Complaints about poor studio production were common,<ref name=BLTA /><ref name=allmusicreview /><ref name=pitchforkreview /><ref name=nyt>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/04/26/arts/david-bowie-mingles-glamour-and-gloom.html | title=David Bowie mingles glamour and gloom | date=26 April 1987 | first=Jon | last=Pareles | accessdate=28 October 2013 | work=The New York Times}}</ref> although publications did find the song to be \"fun\"<ref name=allmusicreview /><ref name=87RSReview>{{cite web | title=\"Never Let Me Down Rolling\" Stone album review | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/never-let-me-down-19870604 | journal=[[Rolling Stone]] | accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> and \"danceable\".<ref name=BLTA /><ref name=Spin87>{{cite journal | journal=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]| title=''Never Let Me Down'' album review | date=May 1987 | first=Glenn | last=O'Brien | pages=29\u201330 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dNSW1RIkidsC&pg=RA1-PA29&dq=bowie&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JBdwUZjtH4moiAK75YH4Ag&ved=0CDQQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=bowie&f=false | accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> Bowie biographer [[Nicholas Pegg]] called the track \"frustrating\", for on one hand being \"a pretty fine song\", but on the other, \"[encapsulating] everything that's initially promising but ultimately infuriating\" about the album. He concluded, \"Somewhere in there is a concerted attempt to reclaim Bowie's former territory of guitar-based rock'n'roll, but 'Day-In Day-Out' suffers badly from over-elaboration: it's a slab of 1980s soft-rock which now [in 2016] sounds incredibly dated by comparison with much of Bowie's earlier work.\"<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" />\n\nB-side single \"Julie\" was described by Bowie biographer David Buckley as the \"catchiest\" song of all the tracks from the ''Never Let Me Down'' sessions, and lamented that the recording was relegated to mere B-side status.<ref name=SFDB>{{cite book|title=Strange Fascination: David Bowie: The Definitive Story|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vk-I_ZM_PfwC&pg=PA374 |accessdate=24 April 2013|last=Buckley|first=David|page=374|publisher=[[Random House]]}}</ref> Pegg agreed, calling it \"arguably one of the best tracks from the whole [''Never Let Me Down'' recording] session\", and thought it might have been a hit if Bowie had released it as a single on its own.<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" />\n\n==Music video==\n===Background and development===\nAn accompanying music video for \"Day-In Day-Out\" was shot in [[Los Angeles]] in early 1987, with Bowie claiming it was \"not going to sell the song at all\", and was designed to explore the music video as a storytelling format over promoting the track itself.<ref name=\"MusicianMag\" /> The singer also took a hand in designing and [[storyboard]]ing the visual, saying, \"I do the original drawings, the main shot for every situation, and then the storyboardist puts them into sequence, storyboarding backwards and forwards from that. Then I put in the major camera angles that I think would be interesting or different. And Julien [Temple] puts in his input. I started working this way on the '[[Ashes to Ashes (David Bowie song)|Ashes to Ashes]]' video with [[David Mallet (director)|David Mallet]]. It was my first real big attempt and it won awards at the time for being a new way of doing videos.\"<ref name=TW87x>{{cite journal | title=Dave In, Dave Out | journal=Music & Sound Output magazine | date=June 1987}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Hollywood_boulevard_from_kodak_theatre.jpg|thumb|250px|right|The music video for \"Day-In Day-Out\" was shot on the [[Hollywood Boulevard]] (''pictured'') at night.<ref name=\"GUK13\"/>]]\n[[Julien Temple]] and Bowie co-directed the video, which made the song's message explicit, showing a young couple's struggle against an uncaring society.<ref name=StockholmPress>{{cite AV media | date=28 March 1987 | title=The Glass Spider Tour Press Conferences (Stockholm)|type=vinyl}}</ref> Bowie worked with Los Angeles theater group \"Skid Row\" to represent the homeless in the video.<ref>{{cite AV media | people=Unknown host | title=Tin Machine (Special) | medium=Television documentary | date=18 October 1991 | location=Copenhagen |minutes=7}}</ref> Tony Selznik taught Bowie to roller skate for the video, recalling in 2013, \"David came across as very humble and in between careers, almost. He was disillusioned with the music industry. I taught him to skate in a parking lot. We shot the video on [[Hollywood Boulevard]] at night, with me in a wig and leather jacket as his double for some scenes. The only bad fall involved the instructor: my wheels came off, I was bleeding everywhere, and David helped me clean up. He was so nice, normal.\"<ref name=GUK13>{{cite journal | url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2013/feb/23/david-bowie-and-me | title=David Bowie and Me | date=22 February 2013 | accessdate=25 June 2013 | journal=[[The Guardian]] | location=London | first=Dave | last=Simpson}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy and recognition===\nThe music video was banned by some TV stations, even after edits removed the female protagonist's heavily implied rape, swapped in an alternate version of a scene where the couple's child spells out \"Mom\", \"Food\" and \"Fuck\" in building blocks (words which represented the child's cycle of dependency; the alternate version had the child spell out the meaningless words \"Mom\", \"Look\" and \"Luck\"),<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" /> and removed a closing scene of a young man urinating on [[Ronald Reagan]]'s star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].<ref name=ct87dido>{{cite journal | url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1987-04-09/features/8701270354_1_david-bowie-video-outlets-absolute-beginners | title=Cleaned Up Bowie`s New Video Is A Hit | date=9 April 1987 | first=Jonathan | last=Taylor | journal=[[Chicago Tribune]] | accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nConcerning the clip's ban, Bowie confessed, \"I think it's ludicrous. [The censors] got caught up in the usual [[Yellow journalism|yellow press]] kind of excitement because of what it looked like instead of what it said.\"<ref name=AmsterdamPress>{{cite AV media | date=30 March 1987 | title=The Glass Spider Tour Press Conferences (Amsterdam)|type=vinyl}}</ref> During the press tour for the [[Glass Spider Tour]], he was asked about the controversy and responded, \"We asked the [Los Angeles] police to work with us and they did very happily. We wanted to indicate how some of the houses for the homeless are removed, so we asked them to bring along the kind of contraption they use [...] it's kind of like a tank with a big battering ram on the end of it. And on the end of the battering ram they've made a little joke. As it goes through the windows it goes 'Have a nice day.' And I pointed out that it would be in the video and they said they were only too pleased to keep it on, so they kept it on. Is that controversial? I don't know.\"<ref name=NewYorkPress>{{cite AV media | date=18 March 1987 | title=The Glass Spider Tour Press Conferences (New York)|type=vinyl}}</ref> The video was nominated for a [[1987 MTV Video Music Awards|1987 MTV Video Music award]] in the category \"Best Male Video\", but lost to [[Peter Gabriel]]'s clip for \"[[Sledgehammer (Peter Gabriel song)|Sledgehammer]]\" (1986).<ref name=mtvvma>{{cite web | url=http://www.mtv.com/vma/1987 | title=MTV Video Music Awards 1987 | date=11 September 1987 | accessdate=28 October 2013|publisher=[[MTV]]}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll lyrics written by Bowie, while remixes produced by [[Shep Pettibone]], except for the \"Groucho\" mix, which was remixed by Paul \"Groucho\" Smykle.<ref name=\"tcdbeu\"/> A limited edition release (EAX 230) of the second 7\" single issued in the United Kingdom contained a 7\" red vinyl disc in a numbered box with a set of stickers and a photo booklet.<ref name=\"12 inch\"/> The video EP is the sole source of the unedited version of the \"Day-In Day-Out\" and \"[[Loving the Alien]]\" videos. While the latter includes a shot of Bowie with a nosebleed, the edited versions of both visuals appear in later video releases.<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" />\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n* '''UK 7\" single''' <ref name=\"7 inch\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=David Bowie \u2013 Day-In Day-Out |url=https://www.discogs.com/David-Bowie-Day-In-Day-Out/master/51369 |website=Discogs |accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Single edit) \u2013 4:14\n# \"Julie\" \u2013 3:40\n* '''UK & worldwide 12\" single 1'''<ref name=\"12 inch\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=David Bowie \u2013 Day-In Day-Out |url=https://www.discogs.com/David-Bowie-Day-In-Day-Out/master/51369 |website=Discogs |accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dance Mix) \u2013 7:15\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dub Mix) \u2013 7:17\n# \"Julie\" \u2013 3:40\n* '''UK & worldwide 12\" single 2'''<ref>{{cite web|title=David Bowie \u2013 Day-In Day-Out |url=https://www.discogs.com/David-Bowie-Day-In-Day-Out/master/51369 |website=Discogs |accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Remix [aka Groucho Mix]) \u2013 6:30\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dub Mix) \u2013 7:17\n# \"Julie\" \u2013 3:40\n* '''US 12\" single'''<ref>{{cite web|title=David Bowie \u2013 Day-In Day-Out |url=https://www.discogs.com/David-Bowie-Day-In-Day-Out/master/51369 |website=Discogs |accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Groucho Mix [aka Remix]) \u2013 6:30\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dance Mix) \u2013 7:15\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Single edit) \u2013 4:14\n# \"Julie\" \u2013 3:40\n* '''US 12\" promo single'''<ref name=\"US2\">{{cite AV media notes |title=Day-In Day-Out |year=1987 |type=Liner notes |publisher=[[EMI]] (Kat.-Nr.: SPRO 9996/9997)}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=David Bowie \u2013 Day-In Day-Out |url=https://www.discogs.com/David-Bowie-Day-In-Day-Out/master/51369 |website=Discogs |accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (7\" Dance Edit) \u2013 3:35\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dance Mix) \u2013 7:15\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Edited Dance Mix) \u2013 4:30\n{{col-2}}\n* '''Video EP'''<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" />\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (video)\n# \"Loving the Alien\" (video)\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dance Version) (video)\n* '''UK digital download''' (2007)<ref name=\"tcdbeu\" /><ref>{{cite web|title=David Bowie \u2013 Day-In Day-Out |url=https://www.discogs.com/David-Bowie-Day-In-Day-Out/master/51369 |website=Discogs |accessdate=8 November 2019}}</ref>\n# \"Al Alba\" [aka Spanish Language version of Day-In Day-Out) \u2013 5:37\n# \"Julie\" \u2013 3:40\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dance Mix) \u2013 7:15\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (Extended Dub Mix) \u2013 7:17\n# \"Day-In Day-Out\" (12\" Groucho Mix) \u2013 6:29\n{{col end}}\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''Never Let Me Down''.<ref name=\"credits\"/>\n* David Bowie&nbsp;\u2013 [[Singing|vocals]], [[composer]], [[Record producer|producer]]\n* [[David Richards (record producer)|David Richards]]&nbsp;\u2013 producer\n* [[Carlos Alomar]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[guitar]]\n* [[Sid McGinnis]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar\n* [[Erdal Kizilcay]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[bass guitar]], [[Drum kit|drums]], [[Electronic keyboard|keyboards]]\n* [[Robin Clark]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]]\n* [[Diva Gray]]&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n* Loni Groves&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|-\n!Chart\n!Peak<br> position\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref name=\"auchart\">{{Cite book|title=[[Kent Music Report|Australian Chart Book 1970\u20131992]] |last=Kent |first=David |authorlink=David Kent (historian) |publisher=Australian Chart Book |location=[[St Ives, New South Wales|St Ives, NSW]] |year=1993 |isbn=0-646-11917-6}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\" |33\n|-\n{{singlechart|Austria|25|artist=David Bowie|song=Day-In Day-Out|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Flanders|10|artist=David Bowie|song=Day-In Day-Out|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true|refname=\"Flanders\"}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Canada|16|artist=David Bowie|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|Finland ([[Suomen virallinen lista]])<ref>{{cite book | first= Timo | last= Pennanen |year= 2006 | title=Sis\u00e4lt\u00e4\u00e4 hitin \u2013 levyt ja esitt\u00e4j\u00e4t Suomen musiikkilistoilla vuodesta 1972 | publisher=Kustannusosakeyhti\u00f6 Otava | location= Helsinki | language= Finnish }}</ref>\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"| 6\n|-\n{{singlechart|Dutch100|15|artist=David Bowie|song=Day-In Day-Out|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|New Zealand|12|artist=David Bowie|song=Day-In Day-Out|accessdate=8 January 2017|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Sweden|5|artist=David Bowie|song=Day-In Day-Out|accessdat