{"title_page": "Laura Mae Lindo", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Laura Mae Lindo\n| image         = Laura Mae Lindo, ONDP MPP for Kitchener Centre.jpg\n| caption       = Lindo at an event during the 2018 Ontario Provincial Election\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|MPP]]\n| office1       = Critic, Citizenship and Immigration Services\n| term_start1   = August 23, 2018\n| term_end1     = \n| leader1     = [[Andrea Horwath]]\n| parliament3   = Ontario Provincial\n| term_start3   = June 7, 2018\n| term_end3      =\n| predecessor3  = [[Daiene Vernile]]\n| successor3    =\n| riding3       = [[Kitchener Centre (provincial electoral district)|Kitchener Centre]]\n| party         = [[Ontario New Democratic Party|New Democratic]]\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1976}} \n| birth_place   = [[Scarborough, Ontario]]\n| residence     = [[Kitchener, Ontario]]\n| occupation    = Non Profit director <br /> post-secondary administrator\n| spouse        = \n| children      = 3\n| alma_mater = [[York University]]\n}}\n'''Laura Mae Lindo''' is a Canadian politician, who was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]] in the [[2018 Ontario general election|2018 provincial election]].<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/ontario-election-2018-kitchener-centre-riding-results-1.4695748 \"NDP's Laura Mae Lindo wins in Kitchener Centre\"]. [[CBLA-FM-2|CBC Kitchener-Waterloo]], June 8, 2018.</ref> She represents the electoral district of [[Kitchener Centre (provincial electoral district)|Kitchener Centre]] as a member of the [[Ontario New Democratic Party]].\n\nShe is the niece of former Ontario MPP and Speaker [[Alvin Curling]]. Prior to her election, she worked as Director of Diversity and Equity at [[Wilfrid Laurier University]].<ref name=Record2018>{{cite news |title=Laura Mae Lindo takes Kitchener Centre |url=https://www.therecord.com/news-story/8658741-laura-mae-lindo-takes-kitchener-centre/ |accessdate=17 September 2018 |work=TheRecord.com |date=7 June 2018}}</ref> She has three children, and holds a PhD in Education from [[York University]].<ref name=Record2018 />\n\nLindo currently serves as a Member of the Standing Committee on Regulations and Private Bills, and as Critic for Citizenship and Immigration Services and Critic for Anti-Racism.<ref>{{cite web |title=Laura Mae Lindo (Kitchener Centre) |url=https://www.ola.org/en/members/all/laura-mae-lindo |publisher=Legislative Assembly of Ontario |accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe is part of Ontario's first ever Black Caucus, alongside NDP caucus colleagues [[Rima Berns-McGown]], [[Faisal Hassan]], [[Jill Andrew]] and [[Kevin Yarde]].<ref>[https://www.ontariondp.ca/news/ndp-establishes-first-official-black-caucus-ontario-history-0 \"NDP establishes first official Black Caucus in Ontario History\"]. [[Ontario New Democratic Party]], April 15, 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ontario MPPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lindo, Laura Mae}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ontario New Democratic Party MPPs]]\n[[Category:People from Kitchener, Ontario]]\n[[Category:People from Scarborough, Toronto]]\n[[Category:Women MPPs in Ontario]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian women]]\n[[Category:York University alumni]]\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n\n\n{{Ontario-MPP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Laura Mae Lindo\n| image         = Laura Mae Lindo, ONDP MPP for Kitchener Centre.jpg\n| caption       = Lindo at an event during the 2018 Ontario Provincial Election\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Provincial Parliament (Ontario)|MPP]]\n| office1       = Critic, Citizenship and Immigration Services\n| term_start1   = August 23, 2018\n| term_end1     = \n| leader1     = [[Andrea Horwath]]\n| office2       = Critic, Anti-Racism\n| term_start2   = August 23, 2018\n| term_end2     = \n| leader2     = [[Andrea Horwath]]\n| parliament3   = Ontario Provincial\n| term_start3   = June 7, 2018\n| term_end3      =\n| predecessor3  = [[Daiene Vernile]]\n| successor3    =\n| riding3       = [[Kitchener Centre (provincial electoral district)|Kitchener Centre]]\n| party         = [[Ontario New Democratic Party|New Democratic]]\n| birth_date    = {{Birth year and age|1976}} \n| birth_place   = [[Scarborough, Ontario]]\n| residence     = [[Kitchener, Ontario]]\n| occupation    = Non Profit director <br /> post-secondary administrator\n| spouse        = \n| children      = 3\n| alma_mater = [[York University]]\n}}\n'''Laura Mae Lindo''' is a Canadian politician, who was elected to the [[Legislative Assembly of Ontario]] in the [[2018 Ontario general election|2018 provincial election]].<ref>[http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/ontario-election-2018-kitchener-centre-riding-results-1.4695748 \"NDP's Laura Mae Lindo wins in Kitchener Centre\"]. [[CBLA-FM-2|CBC Kitchener-Waterloo]], June 8, 2018.</ref> She represents the electoral district of [[Kitchener Centre (provincial electoral district)|Kitchener Centre]] as a member of the [[Ontario New Democratic Party]].\n\nShe is the niece of former Ontario MPP and Speaker [[Alvin Curling]]. Prior to her election, she worked as Director of Diversity and Equity at [[Wilfrid Laurier University]].<ref name=Record2018>{{cite news |title=Laura Mae Lindo takes Kitchener Centre |url=https://www.therecord.com/news-story/8658741-laura-mae-lindo-takes-kitchener-centre/ |accessdate=17 September 2018 |work=TheRecord.com |date=7 June 2018}}</ref> She has three children, and holds a PhD in Education from [[York University]].<ref name=Record2018 />\n\nLindo currently serves as a Member of the Standing Committee on Regulations and Private Bills, and as Critic for Citizenship and Immigration Services and Critic for Anti-Racism.<ref>{{cite web |title=Laura Mae Lindo (Kitchener Centre) |url=https://www.ola.org/en/members/all/laura-mae-lindo |publisher=Legislative Assembly of Ontario |accessdate=17 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nShe is part of Ontario's first ever Black Caucus, alongside NDP caucus colleagues [[Rima Berns-McGown]], [[Faisal Hassan]], [[Jill Andrew]] and [[Kevin Yarde]].<ref>[https://www.ontariondp.ca/news/ndp-establishes-first-official-black-caucus-ontario-history-0 \"NDP establishes first official Black Caucus in Ontario History\"]. [[Ontario New Democratic Party]], April 15, 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Ontario MPPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lindo, Laura Mae}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ontario New Democratic Party MPPs]]\n[[Category:People from Kitchener, Ontario]]\n[[Category:People from Scarborough, Toronto]]\n[[Category:Women MPPs in Ontario]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women politicians]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian politicians]]\n[[Category:Black Canadian women]]\n[[Category:York University alumni]]\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n\n\n{{Ontario-MPP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dylan Spanish", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laura_Mae_Lindo"}
{"title_page": "YF-77", "text_new": "{{Infobox rocket engine\n|name            = YF-77\n|image           =\n|image_size      =\n|caption         =\n|country_of_origin= {{CHN}}\n|date            = \n|first_date      = [[Long March 5|Long March 5 inaugural flight]] (2016-11-03)\n|last_date       =\n|designer        =[[Academy of Aerospace Liquid Propulsion Technology]]\n|manufacturer    =\n|purpose         =sustainer engine\n|associated      =[[Long March 5]]\n|predecessor     =[[YF-75]]\n|successor       =\n|status          = In service\n\n|type            =liquid\n|oxidiser        = [[Liquid oxygen]]\n|fuel            = [[Liquid hydrogen]]\n|mixture_ratio   = 5.5 to 5.45 (adjustable)\n|cycle           = [[Gas-generator cycle (rocket)|Gas-generator]]\n|pumps           =\n\n|description     =\n|combustion_chamber= 1\n|nozzle_ratio    =49\n\n|thrust          = \n|thrust_at_altitude=\n|thrust(Vac)     = {{convert|700|kN|lbf|abbr=on}}\n|thrust(SL)      = {{convert|510|kN|lbf|abbr=on}}\n|thrust_to_weight= \n|chamber_pressure= {{convert|10.2|MPa|psi|abbr=on}}\n|specific_impulse= \n|specific_impulse_vacuum= {{convert|430|isp|sp=us}}\n|specific_impulse_sea_level= {{convert|310.2|isp|sp=us}}\n|total_impulse   =\n|burn_time       = {{convert|465|s}}\n|capacity        =\n\n|dimensions      =\n|length          =\n|diameter        ={{convert|1446|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n|dry_weight      =\n\n|used_in         = [[Long March 5]] core stage.\n\n|references      = <ref name=baike-yf77 /><ref name=wang-2013 /><ref name=nan-2013 />\n|notes           =\n}}\n\nThe '''YF-77''' is China's first [[cryogenic rocket engine]] developed for booster applications. It burns [[liquid hydrogen]] fuel and [[liquid oxygen]] oxidizer using a [[Gas-generator cycle (rocket)|gas generator]] cycle. A pair of these engines powers the [[Long March 5|LM-5]] core stage.  Each engine can independently [[Gimbaled thrust|gimbal]] in two planes.<ref name=wang-2013 /><ref name=sd-lm5 /> Although the YF-77 is ignited prior to liftoff, the LM-5's four strap-on boosters provide most of the initial thrust in an arrangement similar to the European [[Vulcain (rocket engine)|Vulcain]] on the [[Ariane 5]] or the Japanese [[LE-7]] on the [[H-II]]. Like the Vulcain, the YF-77 uses the less efficient gas generator cycle and even for that application it has less performance than the European engine.<ref name=baike-yf77 />\n\n==Development==\nIn January 2002, the development of a new cryogenic engines was approved by the [[Commission for Science, Technology and Industry for National Defense]]. The development responsibility was assigned to the Beijing Aerospace Propulsion Institute, a division of the [[China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation#Subordinate entities|Academy of Aerospace Launch Propulsion Technology]]. The preliminary design was accomplished by mid-2002 and the first set of components was manufactured by early 2003. The same year saw the initial component and subsystem tests, with the gas generator successfully performing its first test on July 30. By December 2003 the whole [[Powerpack (rocket engine)|powerpack]] successfully passed its first integrated test, and on September 17, 2004 a successful 50-second firing of a complete prototype engine was achieved.\n\nIn May 2013 the formal qualification testing campaign began. By the end of 2013 more than 70 tests and 24,000 seconds of firing at steady state conditions had been performed by 12 engines. The concept review confirmed that the performance goal and launcher requirements were met, and the engine was ready for integration for the first launch of the [[Long March 5]] rocket.<ref name=wang-2013 />\nEngine development began in the 2000s, with testing directed by the [[China National Space Administration]] (CNSA) commencing in 2005. The engine has been successfully tested by mid-2007.<ref name=minkang2007 />\n\n==Technical Description==\nThe requirements for an inexpensive, highly reliable, disposable engine are met by using dual {{convert|510|kN|lbf|abbr=on}} (sea level) gas generator engines on a single mounting frame. Each engine has dual turbopumps with separate gas exhaust. Both turbines are fed by a single fuel rich gas generator. The combustion chambers and throat are [[Regenerative cooling (rocket)|regeneratively cooled]], while the nozzle, of welded pipe construction, uses [[Rocket engine#Cooling|dump cooling]]. The turbopumps use solid propellant cartridges for start-up, while the gas generator and combustion chamber use [[Pyrotechnic initiator|pyrotechnic igniters]]. The valves and prevalves are helium-actuated [[ball valve]]s. The thrust and mixture ratio are calibrated with [[Venturi effect|venturis]] and a propellant utilization valve on ground tests. The engine also has dual heat exchanger to supply hot gaseous hydrogen and oxygen for tank pressurization.<ref name=wang-2013 />\n\nAll subsystems are attached to the combustion chamber and gimbal is achieved by rotating the whole engine on two orthogonal planes with two independent actuators. The injector plate uses coaxial injectors, some of which are extended to create baffles that prevent high frequency instabilities. The titanium fuel turbopump uses a two-stage pump with inducer and is actuated by a two-stage axial turbine. It rotates at 35,000 rpm and supplies a discharge pressure of {{convert|16.5|MPa|psi|abbr=on}}. The oxidizer turbopump uses a single-stage centrifugal pump with a helical inducer driven by a two-stage turbine. It rotates at 18,000 rpm and supplies a discharge pressure of {{convert|14|MPa|psi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=wang-2013 />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=baike-yf77>{{cite web |url=http://baike.baidu.com/view/10657947.htm |title=YF-77\u706b\u7bad\u53d1\u52a8\u673a |trans-title=YF-77 rocket engine |accessdate=2015-07-02}}</ref>\n<ref name=minkang2007>{{cite book | isbn = 7542841130 | title = \u795e\u7bad\u51cc\u9704 : \u957f\u5f81\u7cfb\u5217\u706b\u7bad\u7684\u53d1\u5c55\u5386\u7a0b | language = Chinese | trans-title = Divine Arrow Crosses the Sky: Development History of Long March Rocket Series | last1 = Chen | first1 = Minkang | year = 2007 | publisher = Shanghai Science Technology and Education Press | location = Shanghai | last2 = Ru | first2 = Jiaxin | pages = | oclc = 223362195 }}</ref>\n<ref name=sd-lm5>{{cite web |url=http://sinodefence.com/rocketry/changzheng-5/ |title=Chang Zheng-5 (Long March-5) |publisher=SinoDefence |accessdate=2015-07-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703044121/http://sinodefence.com/rocketry/changzheng-5/ |archivedate=2015-07-03 }}</ref>\n<ref name=nan-2013>{{cite journal |last=Nan |first=Zhang |date=2013-09-23 |title=The Development of LOX/LH2 Engine in China |url=http://forum.nasaspaceflight.com/index.php?topic=8447.msg1104075#msg1104075 |journal=64rd International Astronautical Congress, Beijing, China. |publisher=[[International Astronautical Federation]] |volume=IAC-13-C4.1 |issue=1x18525 |pages=5  |format=pdf |access-date=2015-07-02}}</ref>\n<ref name=wang-2013>{{cite journal |last=Wang |first=Weibin |last2=Zheng |first2=Dayong |last3=Qiaot |first3=Guiyu |date=2013-09-23 |title=Development Status of the Cryogenic Oxygen/Hydrogen YF-77 Engine for Long-March 5 |url=http://forum.nasaspaceflight.com/index.php?topic=8447.msg1104075#msg1104076 |journal=64rd International Astronautical Congress, Beijing, China. |publisher=[[International Astronautical Federation]] |volume=IAC-13-C4.1 |issue=2x17679 |pages=7  |format=pdf |access-date=2015-07-02}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.spacelaunchreport.com/cz5.html Space Launch Report]\n\n{{Rocket engines}}\n\n{{Use American English|date=January 2014}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:YF-77}}\n\n[[Category:Rocket engines using hydrogen propellant]]\n[[Category:Rocket engines of China]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rocket engine\n|name            = YF-77\n|image           =\n|image_size      =\n|caption         =\n|country_of_origin= {{CHN}}\n|date            = \n|first_date      = [[Long March 5|Long March 5 inaugural flight]] (2016-11-03)\n|last_date       =\n|designer        =[[Academy of Aerospace Liquid Propulsion Technology]]\n|manufacturer    =\n|purpose         =sustainer engine\n|associated      =[[Long March 5]]\n|predecessor     =[[YF-75]]\n|successor       =\n|status          = In service\n\n|type            =liquid\n|oxidiser        = [[Liquid oxygen]]\n|fuel            = [[Liquid hydrogen]]\n|mixture_ratio   = 5.5 to 5.45 (adjustable)\n|cycle           = [[Gas-generator cycle (rocket)|Gas-generator]]\n|pumps           =\n\n|description     =\n|combustion_chamber= 1\n|nozzle_ratio    =49\n\n|thrust          = \n|thrust_at_altitude=\n|thrust(Vac)     = {{convert|700|kN|lbf|abbr=on}}\n|thrust(SL)      = {{convert|510|kN|lbf|abbr=on}}\n|thrust_to_weight= \n|chamber_pressure= {{convert|10.2|MPa|psi|abbr=on}}\n|specific_impulse= \n|specific_impulse_vacuum= {{convert|430|isp|sp=us}}\n|specific_impulse_sea_level= {{convert|310.2|isp|sp=us}}\n|total_impulse   =\n|burn_time       = {{convert|465|s}}\n|capacity        =\n\n|dimensions      =\n|length          =\n|diameter        ={{convert|1446|mm|in|abbr=on}}\n|dry_weight      =\n\n|used_in         = [[Long March 5]] core stage.\n\n|references      = <ref name=baike-yf77 /><ref name=wang-2013 /><ref name=nan-2013 />\n|notes           =\n}}\n\nThe '''YF-77''' is China's first [[cryogenic rocket engine]] developed for booster applications. It burns [[liquid hydrogen]] fuel and [[liquid oxygen]] oxidizer using a [[Gas-generator cycle (rocket)|gas generator]] cycle. A pair of these engines powers the [[Long March 5|LM-5]] core stage.  Each engine can independently [[Gimbaled thrust|gimbal]] in two planes.<ref name=wang-2013 /><ref name=sd-lm5 /> Although the YF-77 is ignited prior to liftoff, the LM-5's four strap-on boosters provide most of the initial thrust in an arrangement similar to the European [[Vulcain]] on the [[Ariane 5]] or the Japanese [[LE-7]] on the [[H-II]]. Like the Vulcain, the YF-77 uses the less efficient gas generator cycle and even for that application it has less performance than the European engine.<ref name=baike-yf77 />\n\n==Development==\nIn January 2002, the development of a new cryogenic engines was approved by the [[Commission for Science, Technology and Industry for National Defense]]. The development responsibility was assigned to the Beijing Aerospace Propulsion Institute, a division of the [[China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation#Subordinate entities|Academy of Aerospace Launch Propulsion Technology]]. The preliminary design was accomplished by mid-2002 and the first set of components was manufactured by early 2003. The same year saw the initial component and subsystem tests, with the gas generator successfully performing its first test on July 30. By December 2003 the whole [[Powerpack (rocket engine)|powerpack]] successfully passed its first integrated test, and on September 17, 2004 a successful 50-second firing of a complete prototype engine was achieved.\n\nIn May 2013 the formal qualification testing campaign began. By the end of 2013 more than 70 tests and 24,000 seconds of firing at steady state conditions had been performed by 12 engines. The concept review confirmed that the performance goal and launcher requirements were met, and the engine was ready for integration for the first launch of the [[Long March 5]] rocket.<ref name=wang-2013 />\nEngine development began in the 2000s, with testing directed by the [[China National Space Administration]] (CNSA) commencing in 2005. The engine has been successfully tested by mid-2007.<ref name=minkang2007 />\n\n==Technical Description==\nThe requirements for an inexpensive, highly reliable, disposable engine are met by using dual {{convert|510|kN|lbf|abbr=on}} (sea level) gas generator engines on a single mounting frame. Each engine has dual turbopumps with separate gas exhaust. Both turbines are fed by a single fuel rich gas generator. The combustion chambers and throat are [[Regenerative cooling (rocket)|regeneratively cooled]], while the nozzle, of welded pipe construction, uses [[Rocket engine#Cooling|dump cooling]]. The turbopumps use solid propellant cartridges for start-up, while the gas generator and combustion chamber use [[Pyrotechnic initiator|pyrotechnic igniters]]. The valves and prevalves are helium-actuated [[ball valve]]s. The thrust and mixture ratio are calibrated with [[Venturi effect|venturis]] and a propellant utilization valve on ground tests. The engine also has dual heat exchanger to supply hot gaseous hydrogen and oxygen for tank pressurization.<ref name=wang-2013 />\n\nAll subsystems are attached to the combustion chamber and gimbal is achieved by rotating the whole engine on two orthogonal planes with two independent actuators. The injector plate uses coaxial injectors, some of which are extended to create baffles that prevent high frequency instabilities. The titanium fuel turbopump uses a two-stage pump with inducer and is actuated by a two-stage axial turbine. It rotates at 35,000 rpm and supplies a discharge pressure of {{convert|16.5|MPa|psi|abbr=on}}. The oxidizer turbopump uses a single-stage centrifugal pump with a helical inducer driven by a two-stage turbine. It rotates at 18,000 rpm and supplies a discharge pressure of {{convert|14|MPa|psi|abbr=on}}.<ref name=wang-2013 />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=baike-yf77>{{cite web |url=http://baike.baidu.com/view/10657947.htm |title=YF-77\u706b\u7bad\u53d1\u52a8\u673a |trans-title=YF-77 rocket engine |accessdate=2015-07-02}}</ref>\n<ref name=minkang2007>{{cite book | isbn = 7542841130 | title = \u795e\u7bad\u51cc\u9704 : \u957f\u5f81\u7cfb\u5217\u706b\u7bad\u7684\u53d1\u5c55\u5386\u7a0b | language = Chinese | trans-title = Divine Arrow Crosses the Sky: Development History of Long March Rocket Series | last1 = Chen | first1 = Minkang | year = 2007 | publisher = Shanghai Science Technology and Education Press | location = Shanghai | last2 = Ru | first2 = Jiaxin | pages = | oclc = 223362195 }}</ref>\n<ref name=sd-lm5>{{cite web |url=http://sinodefence.com/rocketry/changzheng-5/ |title=Chang Zheng-5 (Long March-5) |publisher=SinoDefence |accessdate=2015-07-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703044121/http://sinodefence.com/rocketry/changzheng-5/ |archivedate=2015-07-03 }}</ref>\n<ref name=nan-2013>{{cite journal |last=Nan |first=Zhang |date=2013-09-23 |title=The Development of LOX/LH2 Engine in China |url=http://forum.nasaspaceflight.com/index.php?topic=8447.msg1104075#msg1104075 |journal=64rd International Astronautical Congress, Beijing, China. |publisher=[[International Astronautical Federation]] |volume=IAC-13-C4.1 |issue=1x18525 |pages=5  |format=pdf |access-date=2015-07-02}}</ref>\n<ref name=wang-2013>{{cite journal |last=Wang |first=Weibin |last2=Zheng |first2=Dayong |last3=Qiaot |first3=Guiyu |date=2013-09-23 |title=Development Status of the Cryogenic Oxygen/Hydrogen YF-77 Engine for Long-March 5 |url=http://forum.nasaspaceflight.com/index.php?topic=8447.msg1104075#msg1104076 |journal=64rd International Astronautical Congress, Beijing, China. |publisher=[[International Astronautical Federation]] |volume=IAC-13-C4.1 |issue=2x17679 |pages=7  |format=pdf |access-date=2015-07-02}}</ref>\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.spacelaunchreport.com/cz5.html Space Launch Report]\n\n{{Rocket engines}}\n\n{{Use American English|date=January 2014}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:YF-77}}\n\n[[Category:Rocket engines using hydrogen propellant]]\n[[Category:Rocket engines of China]]\n", "name_user": "Paine Ellsworth", "label": "safe", "comment": "DisambiguateVulcaintoVulcain (rocket engine)usingpopups", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/YF-77"}
